'''Wooden bullets''' are [[wood]]en [[projectile]]s designed to be fired from a [[gun]]. They are intended to be used as [[non-lethal weapon]]s for [[crowd control]] by enforcing "[[pain compliance]]" at a distance.<ref name=guardian2014>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/12/missouri-police-wooden-bullets-protest-michael-brown|title=Missouri police fired wooden bullets at crowd during protest over teen's death|publisher=The Guardian|date=12 August 2014|author=Jon Swaine}}</ref> They have been known to raise large welts or bruises on their targets.<ref name=guardian2014/><ref name=ACLUM/>
First used by British troops in [[Hong Kong]], and then in [[Northern Ireland]], they are still used by some U.S. police forces for crowd control.<ref name=guardian2014/><ref name=ACLUM>{{cite web|url=http://aclum.org/sites/all/files/education/less_lethal_report.pdf|title=LESS LETHAL FORCE: Proposed Standards for Massachusetts Law Enforcement Agencies|publisher=American Civil Liberties Union of Massachusetts|accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref>
